ey was removed down to approximately 100 ms (30 cm) before expected capture, after which the full buzz sequence was emitted both in air and over water. Bats trawling over water also performed the full capture behavior, but in-air capture motions were aborted, even at very late prey removals (&lt;20 ms = 6 cm before expected contact). Thus, neither the buzz nor capture movements are stereotypical, but dynamically adapted based on sensory feedback. The results indicate that echolocation is controlled mainly by acoustic feedback, whereas capture movements are adjusted according to both acoustic and somatosensory feedback, suggesting separate (but coordinated) central motor control of the two behaviors based on multimodal input. Bat echolocation, especially the terminal buzz, provides a unique window to extremely fast decision processes in response to sensory feedback and modulation through attention in a naturally behaving animal.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Geberl, Cornelia", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Brinkl\u00f8v, Signe", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Wiegrebe, Lutz", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Surlykke, Annemarie", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/db9f89770f750f2dd867491a5c6c5813", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/efec6df09d8294564f9e2b1ee567745a4a8e4ce7215424d6378e86830cc316ec", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/5435545/items/A67SCRY9", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/5435545/items/A67SCRY9", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/04da03067f1c1112fab6bcca4b57eff8!/b92398-94868", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/330417efcaa2560c9b8ebcd6fae17ce0", "rel